‚úÖ PART 1 ‚Äî NOTES (EASY-TO-UNDERSTAND EXPLANATION)
üìå Topic: Joining Multiple Tables in SQL (3 or More Tables)
1Ô∏è‚É£ What is Joining Multiple Tables?

When data is stored in different tables, we use JOINs to combine them into one result.
Joining 3+ tables is just like joining 2 tables ‚Äî you simply add more JOIN statements.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Why Do We Join Multiple Tables?

Real-world data is split into many related tables.

To answer questions like:
‚ÄúWhich customer bought which product and at what price?‚Äù
You need data from Customers + Orders + OrderItems + Products ‚Üí 4 tables.

3Ô∏è‚É£ How Joins Work (Video Explanation)

A JOIN connects rows from one table to another using a common column:

customer_id

order_id

product_id
These act like ‚Äúbridges‚Äù between tables.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Common Types of JOINS Used
INNER JOIN

Shows only matching rows between tables.

If no match ‚Üí row is excluded.

LEFT JOIN

Shows all rows from the first table and matched rows from the second.

If no match ‚Üí values become NULL.

RIGHT JOIN

Opposite of LEFT JOIN.

FULL OUTER JOIN

Shows everything from both tables (matching + non-matching).

5Ô∏è‚É£ Joining More Than Two Tables

Structure looks like this:

FROM table1
JOIN table2 ON conditions
JOIN table3 ON conditions
JOIN table4 ON conditions


SQL reads joins one at a time, left to right.

Each join needs a proper join condition.

Missing condition ‚Üí wrong output or too many rows.

6Ô∏è‚É£ What to Be Careful About

Always join using the correct key.

Outer joins produce NULL values ‚Äî handle them carefully.

Joining many tables can be slow ‚Üí indexing helps.

Use aliases (c, o, oi, p) to make queries readable.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Best Practices

Join only required tables.

Select only required columns.

Use GROUP BY when aggregating (sum, count).

Test query output using smaller datasets first.
